  "prompt": "How is it that the density of water is exactly 1kg/litre?",
  "response": "The density of water being exactly 1 kg/liter is actually a matter of definition and convention, rather than a fundamental physical property. Here's a breakdown:\n\n1. Historical development:\n- In the early metric system, the kilogram was defined as the mass of 1 cubic decimeter (1 liter) of water at its maximum density (4\u00b0C).\n- This definition created a convenient relationship where 1 kg of water occupies 1 liter of volume.\n\n2. Modern definition:\n- Today, the kilogram is defined by the Planck constant, not by water.\n- However, the 1 kg/liter relationship is maintained as a practical standard.\n\n3. Slight variations:\n- Water's actual density varies slightly with temperature:\n  - At 4\u00b0C, it's closest to exactly 1 kg/liter\n  - At room temperature (20\u00b0C), it's about 0.998 kg/liter\n  - When frozen, it's about 0.917 kg/liter\n\n4. Practical significance:\n- This relationship makes water-based calculations in science and engineering very straightforward\n- 1 milliliter of water weighs 1 gram, which simplifies many calculations\n\nSo it's essentially a defined convention that makes scientific and practical measurements more convenient.",
